Strings:
    String Handling Fuctions
    Slicing, indexing
    String Methods
Case conversion

str.upper() – converts all characters to uppercase

str.lower() – converts all characters to lowercase

str.capitalize() – capitalizes the first character

str.title() – capitalizes the first letter of each word

str.swapcase() – swaps uppercase to lowercase and vice versa

str.casefold() – aggressive lowercase (for case-insensitive comparisons)

Search and check

str.find(sub[, start[, end]]) – returns the lowest index of sub or -1 if not found

str.rfind(sub[, start[, end]]) – same as find, but from the right

str.index(sub[, start[, end]]) – like find, but raises ValueError if not found

str.rindex(sub[, start[, end]]) – reverse version of index

str.count(sub[, start[, end]]) – counts occurrences of a substring

Validation / Boolean checks

(check if a string satisfies a certain condition)

str.isalnum() – only letters and numbers

str.isalpha() – only letters

str.isascii() – only ASCII characters

str.isdecimal() – only decimal characters

str.isdigit() – only digits

str.isnumeric() – numeric characters (includes fractions, superscripts, etc.)

str.isidentifier() – valid Python identifier

str.islower() – all lowercase

str.isupper() – all uppercase

str.isspace() – only whitespace

str.istitle() – title case

str.isprintable() – printable characters only

Modification

str.replace(old, new[, count]) – replaces substring occurrences

str.strip([chars]) – removes leading and trailing characters

str.lstrip([chars]) – removes leading characters

str.rstrip([chars]) – removes trailing characters

str.removeprefix(prefix) – removes a specific prefix (Python 3.9+)

str.removesuffix(suffix) – removes a specific suffix (Python 3.9+)

str.expandtabs(tabsize=8) – replaces tabs with spaces

Splitting and joining

str.split(sep=None, maxsplit=-1) – splits string into a list

str.rsplit(sep=None, maxsplit=-1) – splits from the right

str.splitlines([keepends]) – splits on line breaks

str.join(iterable) – joins elements with the string as separator

Alignment and formatting

str.center(width[, fillchar]) – centers the string

str.ljust(width[, fillchar]) – left aligns

str.rjust(width[, fillchar]) – right aligns

str.zfill(width) – pads string with zeros on the left

str.format(*args, **kwargs) – string formatting

str.format_map(mapping) – similar to format but takes a mapping object

Encoding and translation

str.encode(encoding='utf-8', errors='strict') – returns encoded version

str.maketrans(x[, y[, z]]) – creates a translation table

str.translate(table) – translates characters using a translation table
